"Myhre G., Shine K.P., Rädel G., Gauss M., Isaksen I.S.A., Tang Q., Prather M.J., Williams J.E., van Velthoven P., Dessens O., Koffi B., Szopa S., Hoor P., Grewe V., Borken-Kleefeld J., Berntsen T.K., Fuglestvedt J.S.","Radiative forcing due to changes in ozone and methane caused by the transport sector",2011,"Atmospheric Environment","45","2",,"387","394",,,10.1016/j.atmosenv.2010.10.001,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-78649758536&partnerID=40&md5=ec93764aa8679233c4b6e8638dc02b40","Center for International Climate and Environmental Research-Oslo (CICERO), Oslo, Norway; Department of Geosciences, University of Oslo, Norway; Department of Meteorology, University of Reading, Reading, United Kingdom; Earth System Science Dept., UC Irvine, CA, United States; Chemistry-Climate Division, Royal Netherlands Meteorological Institute, Netherlands; Centre for Atmospheric Science, Dept. of Chemistry, Cambridge, United Kingdom; Laboratoire des Sciences du Climat et de l'Environnement (LSCE-IPSL), Gif-sur-Yvette, France; Institute for Atmospheric Physics, University Mainz, Germany; Deutsches Zentrum für Luft- und Raumfahrt, Institut für Physik der Atmosphäre, Oberpfaffenhofen, Germany; Formerly: Deutsches Zentrum für Luft- und Raumfahrt, Verkehrsstudien, Berlin, Germany; Norwegian Meteorological Institute, Oslo, Norway","Myhre, G., Center for International Climate and Environmental Research-Oslo (CICERO), Oslo, Norway, Department of Geosciences, University of Oslo, Norway; Shine, K.P., Department of Meteorology, University of Reading, Reading, United Kingdom; Rädel, G., Department of Meteorology, University of Reading, Reading, United Kingdom; Gauss, M., Department of Geosciences, University of Oslo, Norway, Norwegian Meteorological Institute, Oslo, Norway; Isaksen, I.S.A., Center for International Climate and Environmental Research-Oslo (CICERO), Oslo, Norway, Department of Geosciences, University of Oslo, Norway; Tang, Q., Earth System Science Dept., UC Irvine, CA, United States; Prather, M.J., Earth System Science Dept., UC Irvine, CA, United States; Williams, J.E., Chemistry-Climate Division, Royal Netherlands Meteorological Institute, Netherlands; van Velthoven, P., Chemistry-Climate Division, Royal Netherlands Meteorological Institute, Netherlands; Dessens, O., Centre for Atmospheric Science, Dept. of Chemistry, Cambridge, United Kingdom; Koffi, B., Laboratoire des Sciences du Climat et de l'Environnement (LSCE-IPSL), Gif-sur-Yvette, France; Szopa, S., Laboratoire des Sciences du Climat et de l'Environnement (LSCE-IPSL), Gif-sur-Yvette, France; Hoor, P., Institute for Atmospheric Physics, University Mainz, Germany; Grewe, V., Deutsches Zentrum für Luft- und Raumfahrt, Institut für Physik der Atmosphäre, Oberpfaffenhofen, Germany; Borken-Kleefeld, J., Formerly: Deutsches Zentrum für Luft- und Raumfahrt, Verkehrsstudien, Berlin, Germany; Berntsen, T.K., Center for International Climate and Environmental Research-Oslo (CICERO), Oslo, Norway, Department of Geosciences, University of Oslo, Norway; Fuglestvedt, J.S., Center for International Climate and Environmental Research-Oslo (CICERO), Oslo, Norway","The year 2000 radiative forcing (RF) due to changes in O3 and CH4 (and the CH4-induced stratospheric water vapour) as a result of emissions of short-lived gases (oxides of nitrogen (NOx), carbon monoxide and non-methane hydrocarbons) from three transport sectors (ROAD, maritime SHIPping and AIRcraft) are calculated using results from five global atmospheric chemistry models. Using results from these models plus other published data, we quantify the uncertainties. The RF due to short-term O3 changes (i.e. as an immediate response to the emissions without allowing for the long-term CH4 changes) is positive and highest for ROAD transport (31 mW m-2) compared to SHIP (24 mW m-2) and AIR (17 mW m-2) sectors in four of the models. All five models calculate negative RF from the CH4 perturbations, with a larger impact from the SHIP sector than for ROAD and AIR. The net RF of O3 and CH4 combined (i.e. including the impact of CH4 on ozone and stratospheric water vapour) is positive for ROAD (+16(±13) (one standard deviation) mW m-2) and AIR (+6(±5) mW m-2) traffic sectors and is negative for SHIP (-18(±10) mW m-2) sector in all five models. Global Warming Potentials (GWP) and Global Temperature change Potentials (GTP) are presented for AIR NOx emissions; there is a wide spread in the results from the 5 chemistry models, and it is shown that differences in the methane response relative to the O3 response drive much of the spread. © 2010 Elsevier Ltd.","Aviation; GTP; GWP; Radiative forcing; Road transport; Shipping","GTP; GWP; Radiative forcings; Road transports; Shipping; Aircraft models; Atmospheric chemistry; Atmospheric movements; Aviation; Carbon monoxide; Global warming; Methane; Nitrogen; Ozone; Roads and streets; Ships; Motor transportation; carbon monoxide; methane; nitrogen oxide; ozone; atmospheric chemistry; atmospheric modeling; data set; global warming; methane; ozone; radiative forcing; road transport; shipping; stratosphere; traffic emission; uncertainty analysis; water vapor; article; atmosphere; controlled study; greenhouse effect; priority journal; radiative forcing; water vapor",,"carbon monoxide, 630-08-0; methane, 74-82-8; nitrogen oxide, 11104-93-1; ozone, 10028-15-6",,,,"Balkanski, Y., Myhre, G., Gauss, M., Rädel, G., Highwood, E.J., Direct radiative effect of aerosols emitted by transport: from road, shipping and aviation (2010) Atmos. Chem. Phys., 10, pp. 4477-4489; Berglen, T.F., Berntsen, T.K., Isaksen, I.S.A., Sundet, J.K., A global model of the coupled sulfur/oxidant chemistry in the troposphere: the sulfur cycle (2004) J. Geophys. Res., 109 (D19), pp. D19310; Berntsen, T.K., Fuglestvedt, J.S., Joshi, M.M., Shine, K.P., Stuber, N., Response of climate to regional emissions of ozone precursors: sensitivities and warming potentials (2005) Tellus, 57 (4), pp. 283-3